<subSubSection id="C351A4896477FF8B3BDFFE949C303F01" pageId="4" pageNumber="128" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BF4F7026477FF8B3BDFFE949AAA3D94" blockId="4.[151,1436,150,825]" pageId="4" pageNumber="128">
<emphasis id="B93F2B106477FF8B3BDFFE949C703D78" bold="true" box="[199,584,294,320]" pageId="4" pageNumber="128">Distribution and natural history.</emphasis>
The species was known so far only from in 
<collectingCountry id="F35CB7926477FF8B3F3EFE949A583D78" box="[1062,1120,294,320]" name="India" pageId="4" pageNumber="128">India</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="498F39E06477FF8B3F74FE949B043D78" box="[1132,1340,294,320]" country="India" name="Himachal Pradesh" pageId="4" pageNumber="128">Himachal Pradesh</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="498F39E06477FF8B3E5DFE949EF03D5C" country="India" name="Meghalaya" pageId="4" pageNumber="128">Meghalaya</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion id="498F39E06477FF8B3A1DFEF99FAD3D5D" box="[261,405,330,357]" country="India" name="West Bengal" pageId="4" pageNumber="128">West Bengal</collectingRegion>
) and 
<collectingCountry id="F35CB7926477FF8B3ACDFEF89C203D5C" box="[469,536,330,356]" name="Nepal" pageId="4" pageNumber="128">Nepal</collectingCountry>
(Mid-Western, Western, and Central Regions) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFDA8AF36477FF8B3F2CFEF89AFD3D5C" author="Fauvel, A." box="[1076,1221,330,356]" pageId="4" pageNumber="128" pagination="76 - 112" refId="ref2837" refString="Fauvel, A. (1904) Staphylinides exotiques nouveaux, 2. Revue d'entomologie, 23, 76 - 112." type="journal article" year="1904">Fauvel 1904</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFDA8AF36477FF8B3FC9FEF89BA83D5C" author="Cuccodoro, G." box="[1233,1424,330,356]" pageId="4" pageNumber="128" refId="ref2715" refString="Cuccodoro, G. (2003) A revision of Megarthrus Curtis of India, Nepal and Sri Lanka (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae, Proteininae). In: Cuccodoro, G. &amp; Leschen, R. A. B. (Eds.), Systematics of Coleoptera: Papers celebrating the retirement of Ivan Lobl. Memoirs on Entomology. Vol. 17. International, Gainesville, pp. 359 - 455." type="book" year="2003">Cuccodoro 2003</bibRefCitation>
), and it is reported here for the first time from 
<collectingCountry id="F35CB7926477FF8B399FFEDC9CF23DB0" box="[647,714,366,392]" name="China" pageId="4" pageNumber="128">China</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="498F39E06477FF8B39C0FEDC9DA33DB1" box="[728,923,366,393]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="4" pageNumber="128">Yunnan Province</collectingRegion>
) (
<figureCitation id="1370EB876477FF8B38A9FEDC9DC63DB0" box="[945,1022,366,392]" captionStart="FIGURE 39" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1121,1145]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,345,1061]" captionTargetId="figure-102@9.[151,1436,345,1061]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 39. Distribution map of Megarthrus basicornis Fauvel (pink squares) and Megarthrus budai sp. n. (red circle). Scale bar =200 km." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4321586" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4321586/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="128">Fig 39</figureCitation>
). It occurs at elevations ranging from 
<quantity id="4CB35AE76477FF8B3B8FFE209F703D95" box="[151,328,402,429]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.35" metricValueMax="2.95" metricValueMin="1.75" pageId="4" pageNumber="128" unit="m" value="2350.0" valueMax="2950.0" valueMin="1750.0">1750 to 2950 m</quantity>
a.s.l., mainly in samples of forest leaf litter with decaying wood and fungi.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF4F7026477FF8B3BDFFE049F2A3E04" blockId="4.[151,1436,150,825]" pageId="4" pageNumber="128">
<emphasis id="B93F2B106477FF8B3BDFFE049C5B3DE8" bold="true" box="[199,611,438,464]" pageId="4" pageNumber="128">Comparisons and diagnostic notes.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C4B8C816477FF8B3971FE049D503DE8" authorityName="Fauvel" authorityYear="1904" box="[617,872,438,464]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Megarthrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="basicornis">
<emphasis id="B93F2B106477FF8B3971FE049D503DE8" box="[617,872,438,464]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="128">Megarthrus basicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be easily distinguished from the other 
<taxonomicName id="4C4B8C816477FF8B3E51FE059EE93DCC" baseAuthorityName="Cuccodoro" baseAuthorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Megarthrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B93F2B106477FF8B3E51FE059EE93DCC" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="128">Megarthrus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species known so far to occur in 
<collectingCountry id="F35CB7926477FF8B395AFE689CBD3DCC" box="[578,645,474,500]" name="China" pageId="4" pageNumber="128">China</collectingCountry>
by its uniformly dark brown body color, in combination with the elytra abruptly narrowed basally, and the abdominal pubescence converging on tergites IV-V. Its sexual characters are also diagnostic.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF4F7026477FF8B3BDFFDF49C303F01" blockId="4.[151,1436,150,825]" pageId="4" pageNumber="128">
This species is particularly notable because on the one hand it possesses many features found elsewhere in the genus almost exclusively in members of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C4B8C816477FF8B399FFDD99D213EBC" baseAuthorityName="Paykull" baseAuthorityYear="1789" box="[647,793,618,644]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Megarthrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="depressus">
<emphasis id="B93F2B106477FF8B399FFDD99D213EBC" box="[647,793,618,644]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="128">M. depressus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
supergroup of species, such as the proventral pubescence longer than the metaventral pubescence and the presence of a pair of long posteromedial setae on each abdominal sternite in combination with the absence of a prohypomeral ridge, but on the other hand it lacks a ventral patch of modified adhesive setae on the male first protarsomere (
<figureCitation id="1370EB876477FF8B3800FD649DAE3EC8" box="[792,918,726,752]" captionStart="FIGURES 10-13" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1812,1836]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,848,1788]" captionTargetId="figure-317@4.[151,1436,848,1788]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 10-13. Megarthrus basicornis Fauvel (10-11) and M. budai sp. n. (12-13): Portarsus of male in ventrolateral (10, 12) and ventral (11, 13) views. Ovals indicate absence (red) or presence (green) of ventral patch of modified adhesive setae (green arrows). Scale bar = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4321576" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4321576/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="128">Figs 10-11</figureCitation>
), which is the only character uniquely shared by all the members of this supergroup of species. The presence of a tuft of long setae at base of the aedeagal dorsal valve is unique within the genus.
</paragraph>
